COMPONENT NAME: CKM Teradata
AUTHOR: Oracle
DESCRIPTION This module controls the validity of the constraints of a Datastore and rejects the invalid records in an error table. It can be used for static controls as well as flow controls.
OPTIONS - DROP_ERROR_TABLE: Drop error table before validation? - DROP_CHECK_TABLE: Drop error summary table before validation? - PRIMARY_INDEX: Primary index for error table - COLLECT_STATS: Gather statistics on error table after validation? - CREATE_FLOW_INDEX : Create index on flow table?
LIMITATIONS - Can only be used if the target table/ controlled table has a primary key or an unique key. - Data cleansing can be performed only if a primary key is defined on the controlled table.

When this option is set to YES, the error table will be dropped each time a control is performed on the target table. This means that any rejected records, identified and stored during previous control operations, will be lost.

When this option is set to YES, the SNP_CHECK_TAB check table (which is created in the default Physical Schema of the Physical Server that hosts the controlled table) will be dropped each time a control is performed on the target table. This table contains a collection of all rejected records retrieved from all datastores hosted on the same Physical Server (whatever the Physical Schema may be).

Specify primary index for error table. Teradata uses the PI to spread data accross AMPs. It is important that the chosen PI has a high cardinality (many distint values) to ensure evenly spread data to allow maximum processing performance. Please follow Teradata's recommandation on choosing a primary index, e.g. Teradata Database Design, Chapter "Primary Indexes" When CKM is used inside an interface, best performance is achieved by matching this option with PRIMARY_INDEX option of IKM. Valid options are [PK] Primary key of target table [UK] Update key set in interface, only allowed for flow control [SCD_NK] Natural key of table <list of cols> This comma separated list of target columns defines the primary index. If no value is set (empty), no index will be created. NB: Teradata will automatically choose the first column of the table for the PI. [NOPI] Do not specify primary index for error/check table (Teradata 13.0 & above only).
Collect statistics on primary index of error table?
When this option is set to YES, the existing E$ table and check tables will be dropped and recreate.
This option enables/disables index creation on flow table.
